english:
  title: Elegy for Master Wu Deokjeon
  author: Yi Gyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Master Wu Saejai of Pureyang—whose courtesy name was Deokjeon—was the grandson of the renowned Scholar Yi Hakrin. His family had long distinguished itself through scholarship. He had two elder brothers: Segong and Seomun, with Master Wu as the youngest. All three were celebrated scholars of their age, yet Master Wu shone brightest among them. His brothers themselves acknowledged they could not match his brilliance. When Scholar Yi Jisim married off his daughter to him, though Master Wu occasionally displayed youthful arrogance born of his talents, the father-in-law cherished him too dearly to censure him. He devoted himself entirely to the Six Classics, committing the Book of Changes wholly to memory. Though he did not deliberately memorize the other scriptures, he had internalized nearly half their passages through constant recitation—the words had so impressed themselves upon his lips that they flowed forth unbidden. He once copied the Six Classics by his own hand, saying to others: "A hundred readings cannot compare to the retention gained from a single writing." His poetry and prose embodied the styles of Han Yu and Du Fu. Even ox-herders and menial servants knew his name. In his youth, blessed with such genius, he lived without restraint. Only in his declining years did he pass the examinations, and then did he finally reform himself, becoming a model of propriety and virtue. Yet the world would not receive him. His path grew narrow, and he could not recover. Once he submitted letters to the ministers Zhao and Liu, seeking advancement. His words were poignant and tragic, rising and falling with perfect grace—truly the manner of the ancients. Readers could not help but weep. Yet even this brought no recommendation. How narrow and cruel the world had become! Master Wu perceived that he would never find use in this life. Thus arose in him the resolve to depart. Eastern Capital had been his maternal grandfather's birthplace, and he wished to spend his final years there. But the journey was long and difficult for one on foot. Therefore he sought appointment as a ritual envoy and record keeper, traveled by official post, and decided to remain there, never returning to the capital. In the Eastern City, none had power to protect him. So in poverty and hardship, he passed away. The night before his death, a friend dreamed of him riding a white crane, circling through the heavens. The next day, he went to visit—only to find the Master had already transformed. Alas! In ancient times, even Qu Yuan and Jia Yi, though dismissed and exiled, received their sovereigns' favor and affection in their youth, and could thereby express the fullness of their talents. Li Taibai too was so blessed. Du Fu, though impoverished, at least held the office of Assistant Secretary. Yet Master Wu alone received not even a single appointment before he departed this world. Was it Heaven? Was it Fate? If it was Heaven, how could it bear to make one so talented and virtuous meet such a meager destiny? What principle governs such things? Before Master Wu journeyed eastward, he visited me at my lodge west of the city. He stayed for twelve days, and we discussed our deepest feelings with warmth and sincerity. I was then but eighteen years old, not yet capped as a man, while he was already fifty-three. When I wished to serve him with the respect due to an elder, he would not hear of it. Instead, he proposed that we become friends regardless of age, saying: "The ancients, when forming friendships, considered only the alignment of spirit and purpose—not the count of years. Though my talents do not equal those of Xi Kang, I may well regard you as Ruan Ji." From that time onward, I often joined him in gatherings of poetry and wine. At the assemblies of renowned scholars, he would boast of having gained me as a companion. Some sniped that it was improper for such an aged master of learning to pride himself on friendship with a mere boy. He would simply reply: "You understand nothing of this matter." Thus he showed his regard for me before my talents had yet revealed themselves. I followed him for barely three years, and though I could not fully capture all the fragrance of his orchid-like virtue, I drank deeply of the nectar of his remaining grace. In ancient days, when Tao Qian departed, his students privately granted him the posthumous title "Master Jing Jie." I, though bearing the tender years of a student rather than a formal disciple, have likewise privately bestowed upon him the title "Master Xuan Jing." Thus I compose this elegy:

    Ah, what grace possessed that noble Master!
    A vessel smooth and luminous—
    With shoulders broad as hawks in flight,
    And visage marked by jutting chin and flowing beard.
    When he wielded his brush, the written word
    Flowed forth with ease and piercing clarity.
    The mysteries of the Six Classics pure and deep—
    He plumbed their utmost reaches.
    Where common men can grasp but one tradition,
    He alone held all six within his breast.
    His mind expanded vast,
    Containing all beneath heaven.
    In letters' field, he struck with tiger's force,
    And foes like Han and Du fell at a glance.
    He held his jewels yet never sought to sell them—
    Such was his lot, his nature's own decree.
    Solitary, he dwelt in humble rooms,
    Guarding his poverty with silent grace.
    His sash was tied, his countenance severe,
    His bearing both majestic and composed.
    What need had he for rank and lavish stipend?
    Even the carp that leaps within the stream,
    When freed to water, dances in the tide—
    Yet should it fold its scales in muddy shallows,
    The dragon's form would fade and disappear.
    All self-adornment comes to naught,
    As valueless as cosmetics worn by one of humble birth.
    West Shi herself, though draped in silk,
    Could not be clothed in common thread.
    No minister came forth to praise his merit—
    Should he not then feel shame?
    Yet what mouth remained to speak his cause?
    What hand could loose the chains upon his tongue?
    Talented and virtuous, yet blocked on every path,
    His gaze grew still, his heart grew calm.
    The halls of the great burn bright with power—
    Yet such are flames that feed on emptiness.
    Qu Yuan and Jia Yi faced slander and exile,
    Yet in their youth they shared in government's work.
    But ah, this Master grew old in remote hills,
    Never even tasting droplets of the crown's favor.
    He came to know the bitter tastes the world provides,
    And so resolved to journey forth alone
    Toward the southern reaches of the realm.
    The rivers and lakes lie low and damp—
    No place for one to tarry long.
    He looked instead toward the azure heavens,
    Where a crane became his mount.
    Or perhaps he seeks the three eternal mountains,
    Riding the crane through endless sky—
    Banked by mists of pale azure and rosy clouds,
    Where immortals dwell in their jeweled halls.
    I long to follow in his wanderings,
    Yet am bound by mortal, common clay.
    How could my feet ever lift so light?
    I can but grasp the hem of his robe,
    And offer flowers woven with his name,
    Sealing this remembrance in a sacred text,
    Hoping the blue bird might come at last,
    Bearing these words upward on swift wings
    Toward the place where he now dwells.
